issue.title: First class support for the duration object
issue.body:
It seems to me (forgive me if I'm wrong, I've done my best to take a look at open and closed issues, as well as documentation) that the duration object in the package doesn't have the best support around it.  Comparing them, doing arithmetic on them, etc. seems to not exist at the moment.  This is a little confusing to me, given the awesome simplicity of the `duration` rep.  

Is that something there is appetite for? I would love to add a comparison function for example, among other utilities to make the duration object an esteemed citizen in this library.

pull_request.title: solution and changes for issue #3519
pull_request.body:
### Issue fix #3519. All tests were successfully passed. 

For this issue, I made the following changes:

**1.   subDays/test.ts**
- [x] - Added a test check for subtracting through UTC time.

**2.  addDays/test.ts**
- [x] - Added a test check for adding through UTC time.
- [x] - Deleted offset calculation because it is no longer necessary for the new calculation in addDays/index.ts. (This calculation was used with 4 tests)
- [x] - Deleted the `MINUTE` variable because it is not used now.

**3. addDays/index.ts**
- [x] - Changed the calculation algorithm from `_date.setDate(_date.getDate() + amount)` to a new calculation based on milliseconds. (As was described in the issue description)

**4. addWeeks/index.ts**
- [x] - Deleted the old calculation based on `addDays()` function because this function has new calculation logic now. Changed its calculation for its old algorithm logic  `_date.setDate(_date.getDate() + amount * 7)`. In fact, there was only 1 line added.
- [x] - Deleted the import for `addDays()`, because it is not used now.

**5. nextMondays/tests.ts**
- [x] - Only minor editing of details to make the code consistent. Changed months in the dates so they would be consistent with other functions such as: `nextTuesday()`, `nextWednesday()`, `nextThursday()`, `nextFriday()`, `nextSaturday()`, `nextSunday()`.

issue.title: `startOfWeekWithOptions` (fp module) not strongly typed
issue.body:
In the non-FP module, `startOfWeek` takes a second argument, `options`, which is very strongly typed. `startOfWeekWithOptions` is a function in the FP module that allows you to call `startOfWeek` with the options. But in that function, `options` is NOT strongly typed. It appears to accept _any_ value.

```
// How you're supposed to use it
Dfns.startOfWeekWithOptions({ weekStartsOn: 1 })

// TypeScript does NOT complain about ANY of these
Dfns.startOfWeekWithOptions({ asdf: 1 })
Dfns.startOfWeekWithOptions("banana")
Dfns.startOfWeekWithOptions(undefined)
```
